Question 1

avg_view_sample <- twitch_data %>%
  select(average_viewers, followers) %>%
  sample_n(size = 5)

After selecting 5 random streamers I notice that there is a direct correlation between viewers and followers; the more average viewers you have, the more followers you will gain.

avg_view_summary <- twitch_data %>%
  summarize(average_viewers, followers)
## Warning: Returning more (or less) than 1 row per `summarise()` group was deprecated in
## dplyr 1.1.0.
##  Please use `reframe()` instead.

When using the summarize feature, there isnt a direct correlation between average viewers and followers. The number of average viewers doesnt seem to determine the amount of followers you have.

ggplot(data = avg_view_summary, 
       mapping = aes(x = average_viewers,
                     y = followers)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  labs(title = "Correlation between Average Viewers and Followers on Twitch", x = "Average Viewers", y = "Followers")

twitch_data <- twitch_data %>% 
  mutate(log_viewers = log10(average_viewers), 
         log_followers = log10(followers))

Question 2

fit1 <- lm(log_viewers ~ log_followers, twitch_data)

fit1
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = log_viewers ~ log_followers, data = twitch_data)
## 
## Coefficients:
##   (Intercept)  log_followers  
##        0.1978         0.5885
library(broom)
tidy(fit1)
## # A tibble: 2  5
##   term          estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>            <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)      0.198    0.125       1.58 1.15e-  1
## 2 log_followers    0.588    0.0226     26.0  1.69e-114

Our coefficient is 0.5885. When the raise 1.1 to the 0.6 power, we get 1.0588, therefore a 10% increase in followers is associated with 5.9% increase in the average number of viewers.

Question 3

library(broom)

pred_data <- augment(fit1)
pred_data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = log_followers, 
             y = log_viewers)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.4) + 
  geom_line(aes(x = log_followers, 
                y = .fitted), 
            col = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Followers & Average Viewership", 
       subtitle = "Fitted Model and Raw Data",
       x = "log(followers)", 
       y = "log(viewers)")

I do believe our model describes the relationship well because the regression line follows the general trend of the plots.

pred_data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = log_followers, 
             y = .resid)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.4) + 
  labs(title = "Followers & Average Viewership", 
       subtitle = "Fitted Model and Raw Data",
       x = "log(followers)", 
       y = "Residuals")

There are a few big residuals, around y= 0, with no significant outliers. and they happen between the range of 5 and 6 of our x-variable.

  mutate(language = as.factor(language), 
         language = relevel(language, ref = "English"))

Seeing that most of the other languages have negative means, it can be concluded that English is the most common language amongst viewers.
